2026-04-01 | Surviving Robots Healths After Collisions

Question:
•	You have robots on a line with:
		position, health, direction (L or R)  

•	All robots move at same speed.  
•	Collisions happen when:
		a right-moving robot meets a left-moving robot  

•	Collision rules:
		- lower health robot dies  
		- higher health robot loses 1 health  
		- equal health → both die  

•	Goal:
		find final health of surviving robots in original order.

	Approach
1.	Combine all info into a structure:
		(position, health, direction, original index)

2.	Sort robots by position.

3.	Use a stack:
		store indices of robots moving right (R)

4.	Process robots:
		If direction == 'R':
			push to stack  
		If direction == 'L':
			resolve collisions with stack top  

5.	Collision simulation:
		while stack not empty:
			compare healths  
			handle 3 cases:
				- equal → both removed  
				- stack robot stronger → reduce its health  
				- current stronger → reduce current health and continue  

6.	Track alive robots.

7.	Collect survivors in original order.

	Time Complexity
	O(n log n) (sorting)  
	O(n) (simulation)

	Space Complexity
	O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> survivedRobotsHealths(vector<int>& positions,
                                      vector<int>& health,
                                      string directions) {

        int n = positions.size();

        vector<tuple<int,int,char,int>> robots;

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            robots.push_back({positions[i], health[i], directions[i], i});
        }

        sort(robots.begin(), robots.end());

        stack<int> st;
        vector<int> currHealth(n);
        vector<bool> alive(n, true);

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            currHealth[i] = get<1>(robots[i]);
        }

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){

            char dir = get<2>(robots[i]);

            if(dir == 'R'){
                st.push(i);
            }
            else{

                while(!st.empty() && currHealth[i] > 0){

                    int j = st.top();

                    if(currHealth[j] < currHealth[i]){
                        alive[j] = false;
                        st.pop();
                        currHealth[i]--;
                    }
                    else if(currHealth[j] > currHealth[i]){
                        alive[i] = false;
                        currHealth[j]--;
                        break;
                    }
                    else{
                        alive[i] = false;
                        alive[j] = false;
                        st.pop();
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        vector<pair<int,int>> survivors;

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(alive[i]){
                int idx = get<3>(robots[i]);
                survivors.push_back({idx, currHealth[i]});
            }
        }

        sort(survivors.begin(), survivors.end());

        vector<int> ans;
        for(auto &p : survivors){
            ans.push_back(p.second);
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Only **R vs L interactions matter**.  
Using a stack simulates pending right-moving robots.  

This is similar to:
		"asteroid collision" problem  
but with health reduction logic.
